            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is an Adjustable-Rate Mortgage (ARM)?</h2>
              <p>
                An adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) is a home loan where the
                interest rate can change over time. ARMs usually start with a
                lower fixed rate for a few years (for example, 5 years in a 5/1
                ARM), then adjust periodically based on a market index plus a
                fixed margin.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator helps you understand how your payment might
                change, how rate caps protect you, and how an ARM compares to a
                traditional fixed-rate mortgage.
              </p>

              <h2>How this ARM calculator works</h2>
              <p>The calculator models your loan in three main steps:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Initial fixed period:</strong> Calculates a fixed
                  monthly payment using your initial interest rate and full loan
                  term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rate resets:</strong> After the fixed period, the rate
                  is recalculated at each adjustment interval using:
                  <ul>
                    <li><strong>New rate = index rate + margin</strong></li>
                    <li>
                      Periodic caps limit how much the rate can move up or down
                      at each reset.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      A lifetime cap limits how high the rate can ever go above
                      the initial rate.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Re-amortization:</strong> At each reset, the payment
                  is recalculated so the remaining balance is paid off over the
                  remaining term.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Monthly payment formula (for each segment)
                </p>
                <p>
                  For a given interest rate \( r \) (annual, as a decimal) and
                  remaining term of \( n \) months, the monthly payment \( M \)
                  on balance \( P \) is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( i = \dfrac{r}{12} \) (monthly rate) <br />
                  \( M = P \cdot \dfrac{i(1 + i)^n}{(1 + i)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Interest rate caps explained</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Periodic cap:</strong> Maximum rate increase per
                  adjustment (e.g. 2% per year).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Periodic floor:</strong> Maximum rate decrease per
                  adjustment (optional).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lifetime cap:</strong> Maximum total increase above
                  the initial rate (e.g. +5%).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator applies these caps every time the rate resets, so
                you can see a realistic “worst case” path given your
                assumptions.
              </p>

              <h2>ARM vs fixed-rate mortgage</h2>
              <p>
                ARMs often start cheaper than fixed-rate loans. That can make
                sense if:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You expect to sell or refinance before the first few
                  adjustments.
                </li>
                <li>You believe rates will stay the same or fall.</li>
                <li>
                  You want lower payments in the early years (for example, while
                  your income is lower).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                However, if rates rise, your payment can increase substantially.
                Use the fixed-rate comparison in this tool to see:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  How much interest you might save (or pay extra) with an ARM.
                </li>
                <li>
                  How high your payment could go under your cap structure.
                </li>
                <li>Whether the initial savings justify the potential risk.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The index rate you enter is assumed to stay constant for
                  projections (you can rerun scenarios with different values).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Payments are assumed to be made monthly and on time, with no
                  extra principal payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Taxes, insurance, and HOA dues are treated as level over the
                  life of the loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Actual lender terms (caps, margins, rounding rules) may differ
                  from the simplified model here.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can my ARM payment ever go down?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If the underlying index rate falls, your interest rate can
                decrease at the next adjustment, subject to any periodic floor
                and lifetime floor in your loan contract. In this calculator,
                you can model decreases by lowering the index rate and/or
                setting a periodic floor.
              </p>

              <h3>What is a 5/1, 7/1, or 10/6 ARM?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>First number:</strong> Length of the initial
                  fixed-rate period in years (5, 7, 10, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Second number:</strong> How often the rate adjusts
                  after that (1 = yearly, 6 = every 6 months, etc.).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For example, a 5/1 ARM has a 5‑year fixed period, then adjusts
                every 1 year. To model this, set “Initial fixed-rate period” to
                5 and “Rate adjustment frequency” to 12 months.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I choose my index rate assumption?</h3>
              <p>
                Look up the current value of your loan’s index (SOFR, 1‑year
                Treasury, etc.) and consider whether you want to model a stable,
                rising, or falling rate environment. You can run multiple
                scenarios with different index values to see a range of possible
                outcomes.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I refinance from an ARM to a fixed-rate mortgage?</h3>
              <p>Refinancing can make sense if:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your ARM is about to reset to a much higher rate.</li>
                <li>
                  You plan to stay in the home long enough to recover closing
                  costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fixed rates are attractive compared to your projected ARM
                  rate.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this calculator to estimate your future ARM payments, then
                compare them to a fixed-rate refinance offer (using the
                fixed-rate comparison field).
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-4">
                This tool is for educational purposes only and does not
                constitute financial or lending advice. Always review your loan
                documents and consult a qualified mortgage professional before
                making borrowing decisions.
              </p>
            </section>
